{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493080"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:55:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:55:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1219"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1219"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.02,0.02,0.15,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1219"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103764"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1219"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1219"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86186"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"670"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"2902"},{"type":"tags","id":"2967"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4234"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4303"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6234"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19193"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103764"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of increasing right flank pain, associated with urinary frequency and dysuria. Over the last 24 hours, she has experienced chills and fever. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes, for which she takes metformin. Five days ago, her general practitioner started her on co-trimoxazole for a presumed urinary tract infection. She does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. She is tender in the right flank. Urinalysis shows leucocytes and nitrites. Blood tests are ordered (Images 1-2). Blood and urine cultures are pending.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Non-contrast CT KUB","Cystoscopy","Plain abdominal X-ray","CT - intravenous pyelography (IVP)","Renal tract ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms suggestive of urosepsis, likely secondary to a renal tract pathology such as urinary obstruction from a stone, perinephric abscess, or pyelonephritis. Given her clinical presentation, elevated white blood cell count, and impaired renal function, prompt diagnosis is crucial to guide appropriate management and prevent progression to septic shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-contrast CT KUB\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation in this scenario. It is the gold standard for identifying urinary tract calculi and can also detect other renal tract pathologies such as obstruction, abscesses, or signs of pyelonephritis. Importantly, it does not require the administration of intravenous contrast, which is preferable given this patient\u0027s impaired renal function (as evidenced by her elevated creatinine) and use of metformin (which can increase the risk of contrast-induced nephropathy).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECystoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure that would not be appropriate as the next investigation in an acutely unwell patient with suspected upper urinary tract pathology. It is more useful for investigating lower urinary tract symptoms or bladder pathology and would not provide information about potential kidney or ureteral issues in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlain abdominal X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E has limited utility in this scenario. While it might detect large, radiopaque stones, it would miss radiolucent stones and provide no information about potential obstruction, abscesses, or other renal tract pathologies. Its sensitivity and specificity for diagnosing the cause of this patient\u0027s symptoms are too low to be considered the most appropriate next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT - intravenous pyelography (IVP)\u003C/strong\u003E would provide detailed imaging of the renal collecting system but is contraindicated in this case due to the patient\u0027s impaired renal function and metformin use. The risks of contrast-induced nephropathy outweigh the potential benefits, particularly when non-contrast CT can provide sufficient diagnostic information. Additionally, the inclusion of IV contrast can actually reduce the ability to detect calcium containing kidney stones due to artifact. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal tract ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-invasive option that could potentially identify hydronephrosis or renal abscesses. However, it is less sensitive than CT for detecting urinary tract calculi and may miss smaller stones or other subtle pathologies. Given the severity of the patient\u0027s presentation, a more definitive imaging modality is warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter obtaining a non-contrast CT KUB, the next steps in management would likely include intravenous antibiotics, fluid resuscitation, and potentially urgent urological intervention (such as nephrostomy or stenting) if obstruction is identified. Blood and urine cultures should also be obtained before starting antibiotics to guide targeted therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A non-contrast CT KUB is the preferred initial investigation for suspected renal tract pathology in the context of sepsis and impaired renal function.","Urosepsis requires prompt diagnosis and management to prevent progression to septic shock."],"references":["Kalra OP, Raizada A. Approach to a patient with urosepsis. Journal of Global Infectious Diseases. 2009 Jan;1(1):57. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2840933/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86186"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1219"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15656"},{"type":"media","id":"15657"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15656"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8d46fb05-f49a-4130-bd78-eb732ef7c9b9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8d46fb05-f49a-4130-bd78-eb732ef7c9b9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":188}},{"type":"media","id":"15657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15657"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/736d87c9-32c7-41ad-886e-20a272774c43.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/736d87c9-32c7-41ad-886e-20a272774c43.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":342}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86186"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-26T16:32:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-26T16:32:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1219"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103764"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.e